{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"49864e14-f32d-40b4-9e42-57e99ea4d5d7","content":"## Collecting a CPU Trace on Windows (.NET 8)\n\n**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (lightweight, .NET-aware, no install beyond the global tool).\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (uses the cpu-sampling profile by default)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level ETW events, GC analysis, or deeper kernel-level CPU stacks |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) before committing to a full trace |\n| **WPR/WPA** | Full system-wide Windows Performance Recorder trace (heavy) |\n\n### If you want richer call stacks with PerfView:\n\n```powershell\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500 -ThreadTime\n```\n\n**Start with `dotnet-trace`** — it's the lowest-friction option and gives you managed call stacks immediately. Escalate to PerfView if you suspect native code, kernel, or GC issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a7651225-c367-41a8-a089-47633ebd2621","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question - no code changes or file operations needed.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"680F:1025EC:ABC9CAB:BAC1CFC:69FD3B8A"},"id":"bb609762-d58e-467f-81e3-cde4d05f1d31","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:25:41.441Z","parentId":"5f110306-cf9c-4777-9d64-55c6c4cb454f"}
